Almost one third of the entire worldâ€™s population is infected with Mycobacterium tuberculosis, the type of bacteria that causes TB. Although only a fraction of these people will actually become sick with the disease, in 2012, the World Health Organization reported 1.3 million TB related deaths. The good news is that health care workers and public health officials around the world have done a great job of helping to detect and treat the disease early.  The bad news is that TB is developing drug resistance.  Learn more about this ancient disease, that still plagues us in the modern-day.